<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-028-031 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 442 606</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 28 1991 v25 n43 p77(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Logan says 'I can' to paperless automation. (Logan Aluminum Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vitelo, Jill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Logan Aluminum Inc uses computer-integrated manufacturing to helpit compete against much larger firms by gaining an edge in speedand management.andP;  The company recently integrated its DEC VAX 4000and Modcomp Inc manufacturing minicomputers with its IBM ES/9000and 3090 mainframes to speed data collection and analysis.andO;Reports were previously generated by microcomputers, but todaymetallurgists use minicomputer terminals to connect to an IBMAS/400 database that acts as a centralized information repository.andO;The new system has cut the time required to generate key reportsfrom two weeks to two hours.andP;  The DEC and Modcomp computerscontrol production machinery and generate data about the metal'stemperature, thickness, surface quality and other characteristics.andO;All process control computers are linked to a single AS/400database via Cincom Systems' off-the-shelf Supra package.andP;  Work isunderway to design a second generation of software for the AS/400.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Logan Aluminum Inc. (Automation).andO;Topic:     Computer-integrated manufacturingCase StudyConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>